@startuml fallback-traversal
' One tryWithFallbacks invocation: which checks consume an attempt slot, and how attemptCount threads back out.
' Source of truth: docs/src/gateways/llm/fallback.md
!include _style.puml

start
:**tryWithFallbacks(primary, provider,**\n**request, attemptCount, visited)**\n**primary** is threaded unchanged\nthrough every recursive call;

if (provider.name in **visited**?) then (yes)
  :return **cycle_detected**\nRuntime dedup, defense in depth:\ncycles are already rejected at\nreconcile time;
  stop
else (no)
endif

:visited.add(provider.name);

if (**staticallyEligible**? (checks 1-3)\nsame spec.type / namespace in\nallowedNamespaces / model in models) then (no)
  :**emitFallbackIneligible**\n**(PRIMARY, provider, reason)**\nWarning event on the **primary**\nModelProvider, **not** on the\nprovider that failed the check;
  :return **statically_ineligible**\n**NO attempt slot consumed**;
  note right
    Children of a type-mismatched provider are
    **not** walked either: validation guarantees
    same-type chains, so they stay reachable
    through an eligible ancestor.
  end note
  stop
else (yes)
endif

if (attemptCount >= **maxFallbackDepth**?\n(default 3)) then (yes)
  :return **fallback_depth_exhausted**;
  stop
else (no)
endif

:**attemptCount += 1**;

if (**budgetBlocked**(provider,\nnamespace)? (check 4)) then (yes)
  :**The slot IS consumed.**\nFall through to the children\nwithout forwarding;
  note right
    A budget-blocked **primary** never reaches
    here: it returns **429 budget_exhausted**
    immediately, with no fallback at all, so a
    namespace at its cap cannot drain budget
    from a fallback provider.
  end note
else (no)
  :**forward**(provider, request);
  if (response.ok?) then (yes)
    :**return** response, attemptCount;
    stop
  else (no)
  endif
  if (**isFallbackable**(response)?) then (no)
    :**return** response verbatim\n(400 / 422 / other 4xx):\nno other provider will succeed\nwith the same bad request;
    stop
  else (yes)
  endif
endif

while (next in **provider.spec.fallback**?\n(declared order, depth-first)) is (another)
  :**result, attemptCount =**\n**tryWithFallbacks(primary, next,**\n**request, attemptCount, visited)**;
  note right
    **attemptCount is threaded BACK OUT.**
    Increments inside one subtree are visible
    to the next sibling iteration, so the cap
    bounds the **breadth** of the walk and not
    just its depth. Without the thread-back,
    each sibling would restart from the
    caller's local count and the cap could be
    violated along the breadth dimension.
  end note
  if (result.ok?) then (yes)
    :**return** result, attemptCount;
    stop
  else (no)
  endif
endwhile (none left)

:return **all_fallbacks_exhausted**;
stop

legend bottom
  **Three rules are braided here, and they pull in different directions.**
  A **static** ineligibility skips the candidate and consumes **no** slot, because it is a
  misconfiguration rather than an outage. A **budget** block **does** consume a slot,
  because it is legitimately runtime state and slot-bounded latency still matters.
  And the **FallbackIneligible** event fires on the **primary**, not on the offender,
  because the primary is the resource the platform team owns and watches.
endlegend
@enduml
